SIMPLE: loon
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loon
<hw>Loon</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Scot.
<ets>loun</ets>, <ets>lown</ets>, <ets>loon</ets>; akin to OD.
<ets>loen</ets> a stupid man; prob. for an older <ets>lown</ets>, and
akin to E. <ets>lame</ets>.]</ety> <def>A sorry fellow; a worthless
person; a rogue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loon
<hw>Loon</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[For older <ets>loom</ets>, Icel.
<ets>l⟦omac⟧mr</ets>; akin to Dan. & Sw. <ets>lom</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several aquatic, wed-footed, northern
birds of the genus <gen>Urinator</gen> (formerly <gen>Colymbus</gen>),
noted for their expertness in diving and swimming under water. The
common loon, or great northern diver (<spn>Urinator imber</spn>, or
<spn>Colymbus torquatus</spn>), and the red-throated loon or diver
(<spn>Urinator septentrionalis</spn>), are the best known species. See
<er>Diver</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>looney</ent>⟦br⟧
